Map

It returns a new array from a function for each and every element.  map() does not execute the function for empty elements. 


let arr = [1,2,3,4,5]
let b = arr.map((i)=>{
    return i * 2
})
console.log(`new array returned by map`,b)
new array returned by map [ 2, 4, 6, 8, 10 ]

reduce

It reduces the number of values to a single value. It executed form left to right.

let c = arr.reduce((acc, i)=>{
    return acc+=i
},1) // Here 0 is the accumulator (initial value).
console.log(`new array returned by reduce`,c)
new array returned by reduce 16


filter
The filter() method creates a new array filled with elements that pass a test provided by a function.

let d = arr.filter((i)=>{
    return i%2==0; // condition for filtering the elements in array.
})
console.log(`new array returned by filter`,d)
new array returned by filter [ 2, 4 ]

